WEBVTT

00:31.330 --> 00:32.311
church family.

00:32.592 --> 00:39.320
I am so excited that you're with us today online and if you've just discovered us online, I'm so glad that you're connecting with us also.

00:39.821 --> 00:46.489
My name is Steve and I'm part of the worship team here at Heritage and I get excited when I get to play, when I get to sing for the Lord.

00:46.850 --> 00:59.346
One of my favorite scriptures I want to share with you is praise him with the sound of trumpets, praise him with the harp and the lyre, praise him with the cymbals, praise him with strings and flute, praise him with dance.

00:59.842 --> 01:07.623
I love to worship and I'm going to invite you into a time of worship now as we sing, as we worship and we praise our Lord.

01:08.125 --> 01:14.482
Why don't you join us and sing along with us and love the Lord through song.

01:36.066 --> 02:04.754
Don't mix around Just one word The darkness has to retreat Just one text I feel the presence of heaven Just one text My eyes are open to see

02:04.962 --> 02:32.722
My heart can't help but believe There's nothing that I can't do There's not a mountain that he can move Or praise the name that makes a way There's nothing that I can't do Just one word, just one word You hear what's broken inside

02:37.058 --> 03:04.050
Just one word and you revive every dream Just one touch But just one touch I feel the power of heaven Yeah, it's just one touch My eyes are open to see My heart can't help but believe that There's nothing left

03:55.202 --> 04:21.426
There's no power like the power of Jesus Let faith arise Let all agree There's no power like the power of Jesus I will believe For greater things There's no power like the power of Jesus Let faith arise

04:22.658 --> 04:26.802
So power like the power of Jesus

15:31.266 --> 15:37.254
And it has been such a great time spending these last few moments worshiping with you.

15:37.855 --> 15:44.985
We've proclaimed the Lord's faithfulness, but we've also proclaimed our own need for stronger and more robust faith.

15:45.625 --> 15:56.320
And hopefully these moments together help us gather strength so that we can live with Christ-like love and represent Him well in our homes, schools, and workplaces.

15:57.061 --> 16:00.946
And I was thinking this week about desperation and desires

16:01.058 --> 16:07.267
how those two things have a significant effect on what I choose to focus on and sort of work towards.

16:07.908 --> 16:16.259
As a kid, I remember there were like certain toys like the GI Joe aircraft carrier or video game like Mario or movies like Return of the Jedi.

16:16.279 --> 16:20.245
I just could not wait to experience and maybe interact with.

16:20.305 --> 16:23.910
And I'd go through seasons where I was so fixated on a certain thing.

16:24.651 --> 16:29.778
And whatever it happened to be, usually I would spend a lot of time just fixating

16:29.890 --> 16:41.848
and thinking about those things, which is why I think we often see the scriptures use language around longing and desire because our longings tend to define our focus.

16:42.388 --> 16:46.034
In fact, listen to how the beginning of Psalm 84 sounds.

16:46.735 --> 16:51.462
How lovely is your dwelling place, O Lord of Heaven's armies.

16:52.223 --> 16:57.170
I long, yes, I faint with longing to enter the courts of the Lord.

16:57.474 --> 17:02.621
With my whole being, body and soul, I will shout joyfully to the living God.

17:03.622 --> 17:07.147
It reminds me of a really great prayer that was written by A.W.

17:07.187 --> 17:09.550
Tozer, found in his book, The Pursuit of God.

17:10.010 --> 17:19.743
Some of the language has been adapted a little bit, but I want to encourage you to listen to the language of longing and desire that Tozer uses.

17:20.244 --> 17:25.010
It might even seem a bit strange to you if you've never used this type of language with God before.

17:25.218 --> 17:41.036
But I would just encourage you to allow these words to frame your own prayers and allow God to sort of plant a seed of longing in your heart for your desperation for him to grow desperation to know more of him and the desperation to be known by him.

17:41.596 --> 17:44.459
So allow me to pray this beautiful prayer over us.

17:45.821 --> 17:54.130
Oh God, I have tasted your goodness and it has both satisfied me and made me thirsty for more.

17:54.818 --> 17:58.403
I am painfully conscious of my need, a further grace.

17:59.024 --> 18:01.368
I am ashamed of my lack of desire.

18:02.149 --> 18:05.754
O God, the triune God, I want to want you.

18:05.774 --> 18:08.258
I long to be filled with longing.

18:08.398 --> 18:11.282
I thirst to be made more thirsty still.

18:12.203 --> 18:13.445
Show me your glory.

18:13.786 --> 18:14.627
I pray to you.

18:15.428 --> 18:18.172
So I may know you indeed.

18:19.053 --> 18:22.258
In your mercy, begin a new work of love within me.

18:22.658 --> 18:33.673
Say to my soul, rise up my love, my fair one, and come away, and then give me grace to rise and follow you from this misty lowland where I have wandered so long.

18:34.614 --> 18:35.616
We pray these things.

18:36.296 --> 18:38.680
In Jesus' name, amen.

18:51.978 --> 18:52.178
It's over.

18:54.050 --> 18:57.074
It's never over.

20:24.450 --> 20:27.079
I guess I'm supposed to welcome you to the danger zone.

20:27.742 --> 20:32.920
How many of you are insanely jealous of our team and the things that they can do?

20:32.940 --> 20:35.890
They're awesome.

20:37.090 --> 20:50.422
I love our team, I love that I get to be a part of conversations like this one where we take, you know, really a series of serious conversations but have some fun with them as we unpack God's word together.

20:50.442 --> 20:56.707
As Pastor Steve mentioned, we're stepping into a new series called At the Movies and the reality is movies have changed, right?

20:56.727 --> 21:07.076
Instead of always having to go to the movies, they are coming to us and how we choose to interact with those, the movies that we watch, the stories that we tell, they all share

21:07.056 --> 21:08.690
little bit about

21:08.770 --> 21:13.794
It's kind of a window into who we are and how we view the world.

21:13.854 --> 21:17.317
This week, as we mentioned, we're looking at action and adventure.

21:17.558 --> 21:22.482
And I think, you know, action and adventure movies for me fall into one of two categories.

21:22.982 --> 21:29.448
One is one that you can watch and enjoy with absolutely no thought process at all, right?

21:29.688 --> 21:35.773
There are plot holes so large you could fly some of those jets through them, and it's just there to be enjoyed.

21:35.793 --> 21:38.756
But then there are other action and adventure movies.

21:38.736 --> 21:44.981
that get your blood pumping, that kind of get you connecting with the main character of the story.

21:45.021 --> 21:59.134
Because there's something for us, there's something about watching this ordinary person usually up against all odds, working to risk everything for the sake of something greater than themselves.

21:59.394 --> 22:08.722
I think the more I interact with stuff like action and adventure, the more I'm aware of my own heart's desire to be part of an adventurous life.

22:09.090 --> 22:14.857
to live into something that is greater than the story I might tell on my own.

22:14.897 --> 22:16.920
I think we all resonate with that.

22:16.940 --> 22:31.418
I think from time to time, each and every one of us have these moments where it's in the still quiet moments of the night as we're drifting off into sleep, this quickening of our heart that says there's got to be something more.

22:31.758 --> 22:34.842
There's got to be stuff that matters.

22:34.922 --> 22:37.906
And I think action and adventure, the movies,

22:37.954 --> 22:40.096
They kind of salve that for us a little bit.

22:40.116 --> 22:53.788
Some of us were so looking for the life that matters of adventure and purpose and meaning that we'll go and create moments of adventure in all kinds of other spaces and ways just to feel the thrill of action.

22:54.088 --> 22:55.569
My dad is one of those people.

22:55.830 --> 23:04.937
And when he would spend time with us, which was rare, but when he would spend time with us, he would often take us to some space of action and adventure.

23:04.957 --> 23:07.940
And so on one particular trip, when I was just a young teenager,

23:07.920 --> 23:20.938
He gathered my brother, sister, and I, his fiancé, my aunt, and my Tia, and her kids, and we all went to the Dragoon Mountains in southeastern Arizona, which is probably a space you've never heard of.

23:21.239 --> 23:29.170
But what they are are these boulders and outcroppings of rock that people go mountain climbing, or rock climbing on all the time.

23:29.410 --> 23:32.858
And my dad was a rescue and recovery climber.

23:33.118 --> 23:43.762
So he would like to go and kind of keep his skills up to date and thought it would be great fun to invite all of his family to come and go climbing with him.

23:44.034 --> 23:52.525
Now the thing is that all of my cousins, my thea and her family, my dad and his fiance, they all had hours and hours of experience doing this.

23:52.585 --> 23:56.891
My brother, sister and I, we had never been rock climbing before at all.

23:57.291 --> 24:06.884
And so I remember getting to the space that they had kind of preset for the space for us to go climbing and getting into a harness and getting all excited about what this was gonna be.

24:07.144 --> 24:08.646
And my dad immediately said, stop.

24:09.407 --> 24:11.890
No, no, this isn't for you yet.

24:12.258 --> 24:21.490
You and your siblings, you're going over there to what I would call the kitty pool of rock climbing, okay?

24:21.602 --> 24:22.603
was embarrassing.

24:22.623 --> 24:23.605
It was humiliating.

24:23.645 --> 24:26.269
It was like just a little tiny rock in the desert floor.

24:26.349 --> 24:30.254
But he said, you know, you've got to get used to some hand holds and stuff like that.

24:30.274 --> 24:33.138
So I'll come over there and I'll tell you what to do in a little bit.

24:33.218 --> 24:38.406
And my brother and sister and I went over there embarrassed and frustrated because we wanted to be part of the action over here.

24:38.846 --> 24:41.891
And he took longer than we thought he should have.

24:42.071 --> 24:47.058
And so eventually, I saw another outcropping like over there.

24:47.234 --> 24:52.320
and I grabbed my brother and sister, and I said, let's go show that we don't need to do this thing over here.

24:52.380 --> 24:53.461
We're ready for it, okay?

24:53.902 --> 25:06.015
And we worked hard to, I mean, I remember just sweat dripping down, being all scraped and scratched up, as I finally got about six inches off the desert floor, you know, just like getting that.

25:06.316 --> 25:15.506
And then finally, like, I felt like, yes, I'm getting some traction, and I'm telling my brother and sister, this is what you ought to do, because as the oldest, I'm the expert, even though I'd never done this before.

25:15.842 --> 25:16.985
younger children in the room.

25:17.025 --> 25:18.208
You know how that works, right?

25:18.308 --> 25:20.013
Your older sibling is always the expert.

25:20.033 --> 25:21.075
I said, so this is what we're going to do.

25:21.376 --> 25:25.286
And I remember reaching up into kind of a next handhold.

25:25.748 --> 25:29.437
Remember, this is in the desert in the southeastern part of Arizona.

25:29.678 --> 25:32.946
And something wriggled under my hand, okay?

25:33.570 --> 25:35.732
If it riggles in the desert, it's bad.

25:35.773 --> 25:38.776
There's nothing that slithers that's good in the desert.

25:39.076 --> 25:45.624
And so I kind of like, I let go and I fell back hard on my butt and, you know, kind of saw stars.

25:45.864 --> 25:48.908
And at that point, my sister decided she was done with this.

25:49.168 --> 25:49.949
And she just disappeared.

25:49.969 --> 25:50.670
I don't know where she went.

25:50.710 --> 25:51.170
She was done.

25:51.551 --> 26:00.301
My brother made sure I was fine and then went back to where my dad was to see if he could learn to climb there.

26:00.521 --> 26:01.362
I have to tell you,

26:01.794 --> 26:06.835
I did not feel that day like I had been part of a great action-adventure space, right?

26:07.156 --> 26:09.485
It was like a comedy of errors more than anything.

26:09.546 --> 26:11.634
Now, we're gonna come back to that in a little bit.

26:11.874 --> 26:24.025
But I think for us, we all have these spaces and places where we want to be part of action and adventure of something that matters, something where it feels like everything's on the line, but it could change everything for us.

26:24.366 --> 26:30.972
The reason we resonate so much with action and adventure stories is because that's part of the story I believe we are to live.

26:31.272 --> 26:34.595
And God has wired us to resonate with that.

26:34.615 --> 26:35.737
So here's the question.

26:36.117 --> 26:41.522
If we're wired that way, if we're made for that, how come it can seem so distant?

26:41.666 --> 26:42.047
from us.

26:42.407 --> 26:50.600
How come a life of purpose and adventure and meaning going to bed at the end of the day knowing we were spent in the very best way possible to wake up and do it all again?

26:50.881 --> 26:54.747
How can that seem just out of reach so much of the time?

26:55.388 --> 26:57.592
There's actually a passage in Scripture.

26:57.832 --> 27:06.546
We're going to be in Mark chapter 10 for most of our time together and there's this passage in Scripture where Jesus has been doing incredible ministry and

27:07.298 --> 27:17.411
There's this question posed to him that is basically, in a sense, how do I live the life of purpose and adventure and meaning that I'm made for?

27:17.751 --> 27:21.976
We pick it up in Mark chapter 10, verse 17.

27:22.036 --> 27:27.904
It says, as Jesus started on his way, a man ran up to him and fell on his knees before him.

27:28.384 --> 27:29.746
Good teacher, he asked.

27:29.922 --> 27:32.826
What must I do to inherit eternal life?

27:32.966 --> 27:39.836
In other words, I think of the way we would say it today is, what must I do to live the life I'm made for?

27:40.236 --> 27:45.023
What must I do to connect in that space of purpose and adventure and meaning?

27:45.043 --> 27:51.372
Because every time Jesus talked about eternal life, he wasn't talking about simply going to heaven after we die.

27:51.412 --> 27:56.079
He was talking about experiencing fullness of life here and now.

27:56.619 --> 27:57.581
So what do I have to do?

27:57.641 --> 27:58.482
How do I do that?

27:59.138 --> 28:01.180
And Jesus answers, why do you call me good?

28:01.881 --> 28:03.462
No one is good except God alone.

28:03.502 --> 28:05.945
He's kind of indicating something about his own identity here.

28:06.646 --> 28:07.847
You know the commandments.

28:08.207 --> 28:09.248
You shall not murder.

28:09.328 --> 28:10.750
You shall not commit adultery.

28:10.770 --> 28:11.851
You shall not steal.

28:11.911 --> 28:13.552
You shall not give false testimony.

28:13.773 --> 28:14.954
You shall not defraud.

28:15.434 --> 28:17.316
Honor your father and your mother.

28:17.356 --> 28:22.441
Teacher, the man declared, all these I have kept since I was a boy.

28:23.442 --> 28:27.026
Jesus looked at him and loved him.

28:28.226 --> 28:33.174
One thing you lack, he said, go sell everything you have and give it to the poor.

28:33.876 --> 28:34.997
And you'll have treasure in heaven.

28:35.819 --> 28:36.901
Then come follow me.

28:38.183 --> 28:40.647
At this, the man's face fell.

28:41.729 --> 28:45.916
He went away sad because he had great wealth.

28:46.998 --> 28:54.290
In the scriptures, this same story is told three times in the Book of Matthew, in the Mark, in the Book of Mark, and in the Book of Luke.

28:55.010 --> 29:05.648
Each time this man, called the rich young ruler in other texts, this man runs up to Jesus and asks him, what must I do to inherit eternal life?

29:05.708 --> 29:11.858
He looks eternal life in the ever-living face and ends up walking away sad.

29:12.514 --> 29:27.830
He ends up looking in the face, the very answer to the question that he has, and somehow ends up walking away sad because he trusts more in the stuff he has built than in the invitation of Jesus before him.

29:28.310 --> 29:30.592
This happens time after time after time.

29:30.793 --> 29:39.922
And part of the reason I think this is included, not once, not twice, but three times, is not so that we walk away going, well, that's weird.

29:40.194 --> 29:41.897
Why would that be there?

29:42.218 --> 29:48.069
I think it's included because of this kind of central truth that we're going to spend our time interacting with today.

29:48.089 --> 29:57.586
It's when it comes to the things of adventure, of life, of purpose and meaning, the stuff of Jesus in his kingdom, we don't have to walk away sad.

29:58.242 --> 30:00.124
We don't have to walk away sad.

30:00.384 --> 30:10.615
The reason this story is included is not because the man's story needs to be our story, but because you and I are invited to take a different path.

30:10.636 --> 30:24.090
We're invited to interact in a way where we actually step into the gift of eternal life that Jesus offers, where we actually receive the purpose and action and adventure that we're meant for, that we do at the end of the day.

30:24.551 --> 30:27.634
Feel like, man, I have been spent in the very best way.

30:27.746 --> 30:28.327
possible.

30:29.048 --> 30:40.765
I'm convinced that you and I don't have to go another day, another moment, without experiencing and knowing what that means to find joy and fulfillment and adventure in the life that we lived.

30:41.566 --> 30:44.110
We don't have to walk away sad.

30:45.472 --> 30:52.082
Now, the key to understanding how we get there is actually in the passage of Scripture just before this.

30:52.322 --> 30:57.047
Because as I said, this passage is included three times in Matthew, Mark, and Luke.

30:57.107 --> 31:06.375
And every time it's told, not just once or twice, but every time it's told, it comes on the heels of another moment in the life of Jesus.

31:06.396 --> 31:11.420
It's actually set up to walk in parallel, to see the contrast of these two moments.

31:11.741 --> 31:21.490
So there's the rich young ruler who falls before Jesus, the rich young ruler who even the disciples, as they see him coming, think, now here's a guy who has it all figured out.

31:21.762 --> 31:26.547
Here's the guy who, if anybody's gonna find purpose and adventure and meaning, the kingdom of Jesus.

31:26.567 --> 31:32.013
It is this guy, because he is powerful, he is young, he is wealthy, he's got it.

31:32.153 --> 31:34.775
He just needs to unlock a little peace.

31:35.056 --> 31:35.997
He's not far.

31:36.097 --> 31:38.780
It's what the disciples think, even just a moment later.

31:39.781 --> 31:49.010
Now, it comes on the heels of a space where Jesus is teaching, and these parents start bringing their little kids up to Jesus.

31:49.218 --> 31:54.885
They start bringing their children before Jesus so that he can bless them and teach them as well.

31:55.185 --> 32:02.774
And the disciples know what you and I may not know about life in this season of life in the Scriptures.

32:03.195 --> 32:09.382
That children in that day and age were seen as almost worthless parts of society.

32:09.762 --> 32:12.786
That they could offer nothing.

32:13.282 --> 32:15.968
They were simply resource consumers.

32:16.309 --> 32:17.752
They weren't contributors.

32:17.772 --> 32:19.736
They could inherit no land.

32:19.776 --> 32:21.560
They could speak not for their parents.

32:21.841 --> 32:29.938
They were actually often literally tossed in the trash heap if their parent stopped being able to provide for them.

32:30.114 --> 32:36.643
There is no value given to children, especially the kind of little children that the scripture is speaking of here.

32:36.923 --> 32:46.296
Now for some of us that might shock our sensibilities, but for the listeners of scripture in Jesus' day, they knew that these kids, they're not gonna contribute anything.

32:46.556 --> 32:54.707
So the disciples go in and they stop the parents from bringing their kids because Jesus has more important things to do, all right?

32:55.028 --> 32:59.794
This is what's happening right before the rich young man, the rich young ruler approaches

32:59.906 --> 33:00.407
Jesus.

33:00.788 --> 33:09.589
But then we pick up the story a little bit before it says, when Jesus saw this, the disciples pushing away the kids and the parents, he was indignant.

33:10.671 --> 33:12.576
When Jesus saw this, he was indignant.

33:12.656 --> 33:14.961
This is the one time in the book of Mark.

33:15.262 --> 33:18.610
It's the one time that we see Jesus get angry.

33:19.234 --> 33:22.278
Like that we see Jesus described as indignant.

33:22.558 --> 33:25.702
Yep, there's a space in place where he flips tables in the temple.

33:26.002 --> 33:31.029
Yep, there's a space in place where he corrects the religious leaders who are putting two heavy a burden on people.

33:31.309 --> 33:36.455
But it's this one time that Jesus is expressed as being indignant.

33:36.536 --> 33:39.379
And it's when it comes to these children.

33:39.459 --> 33:42.263
He said to them, let the little children come to me.

33:42.663 --> 33:43.504
Do not hinder them.

33:43.825 --> 33:48.210
For the kingdom of God belongs to such as these.

33:50.722 --> 33:59.396
These children who have no standing are the very same ones that Jesus says are the ones who actually will inherit his kingdom.

33:59.857 --> 34:02.441
He says, the kingdom of heaven actually belongs to such a season.

34:02.461 --> 34:07.529
If you want to receive my kingdom, you have to enter into it like one of these.

34:07.890 --> 34:09.553
It's two very different pictures.

34:10.574 --> 34:15.282
One of somebody we would say has nothing to offer and one of somebody who has everything to offer.

34:16.866 --> 34:18.829
and the script gets flipped for us.

34:19.029 --> 34:35.451
And I think it speaks directly to how you and I can actually step in, no matter the stage of life that we're in, no matter what our story has been up until this point, that we can step in to the life of adventure and purpose and meaning that God has for us.

34:37.214 --> 34:40.498
Jesus gave the rich young ruler a call to adventure.

34:40.770 --> 34:45.218
Jesus actually created space for the children to enter into his kingdom.

34:45.358 --> 34:56.176
And what we see in those two pictures is that Jesus' call to adventure moves us from first focusing on what we're owed to what we surrender.

34:56.737 --> 35:06.514
You see, the call of adventure in Jesus shifts our heart, our mind, our thinking and our view to moving from what we're owed to what we surrender.

35:07.042 --> 35:17.094
There's a sense, if you read the scripture here, that the rich young ruler, actually, though he comes in a posture of humility, has a sense of expectation.

35:17.955 --> 35:21.960
One, he interrupts whatever it is Jesus is doing to have this conversation.

35:22.440 --> 35:29.068
Two, he is fully expectant that Jesus is going to do the thing that he's asking for, which isn't a bad thing.

35:30.430 --> 35:34.194
But it seems to me, as we unpack the story, that there's

35:34.466 --> 35:38.451
There's actually a sense of maybe what this man is owed.

35:40.655 --> 35:47.123
And instead, Jesus invites him to move from what he thinks he's owed to what he can surrender.

35:48.165 --> 35:50.128
And I think that's the case for you and for me.

35:50.989 --> 35:59.180
The children that were being interacted with with Jesus just the moment before, everyone would say they had nothing to offer, but Jesus wanted them to gain everything.

36:00.242 --> 36:03.506
Jesus looked at the rich young ruler who approached him and he loved him.

36:03.938 --> 36:09.968
and made an invitation for him, the invitation was to surrender a part of his life.

36:10.268 --> 36:19.182
In fact, in another translation of this same passage, Jesus says it's difficult for those who put their trust in riches.

36:20.244 --> 36:23.108
It wasn't that the man was wealthy that was his problem.

36:23.389 --> 36:28.537
It was where he placed his trust and expectancy and expectation.

36:29.939 --> 36:31.762
And so here we see this

36:31.874 --> 36:41.529
interaction where we start, if we peel back the layers to understand that Jesus called to adventure, moves us from seeking comfort to embracing risk.

36:41.690 --> 36:44.154
I'm sorry, from focusing on what we're owed to what we surrender.

36:45.716 --> 36:52.427
And then it shifts us from seeking comfort to embracing risk.

36:53.449 --> 36:57.896
So the rich young ruler moves from what he expects to what he surrenders.

36:58.196 --> 36:59.378
This is what the invitation is.

37:00.866 --> 37:08.377
And we also see that he's in being invited in that same space to leave his comfort behind for risk.

37:08.938 --> 37:15.367
If he trusts in his wealth primarily, then he has great comfort if nothing changes for him.

37:15.387 --> 37:26.002
But if he's invited instead to step away from the thing that he trusts most so that he can experience something greater from Jesus, well then everything can change for him.

37:27.554 --> 37:34.264
I think there are times for you and for me when we approach God as though he owes us something.

37:35.625 --> 37:48.764
And then when we're, when we don't receive that thing that we feel we're owed because we've done the right thing, said the right thing, been obedient in the right ways, whatever it may be, that then we kind of retreat into comfort.

37:49.225 --> 37:55.794
We retreat into the spaces that are known and comfortable, but here's the thing with action and adventure.

37:55.970 --> 37:59.199
Comfort and action can't coexist.

38:00.082 --> 38:01.807
They don't live together.

38:02.449 --> 38:09.650
If you step into a space of adventure, you are inherently, by definition, leaving the space of comfort.

38:10.370 --> 38:17.958
And so some of us, what happens is we try to find counterfeit spaces of adventure, because our hearts long for it.

38:18.159 --> 38:19.040
We're made for it.

38:19.240 --> 38:25.367
We want to know we're living in a space that matters, contributing something far beyond ourselves.

38:25.787 --> 38:39.122
But because it requires us to shift from what we're owed to what we surrender and from the space of comfort to risk, we might find a sweet substitute for it.

38:39.554 --> 38:44.222
instead of actually receiving what Jesus is inviting us into.

38:45.303 --> 38:53.597
Jesus interacted with this rich young ruler who wanted the comfort of eternal life without the risk of kingdom living.

38:54.398 --> 38:56.762
That's what came down to in a nutshell.

38:58.124 --> 39:05.136
You see, Jesus invites us to shift our mind, our heart from the space of comfort to risk.

39:05.156 --> 39:06.418
What do you think would have happened?

39:07.170 --> 39:14.938
What do you think would have happened if this rich young ruler had said, okay, I'll try it.

39:15.158 --> 39:15.979
Let's see what happens.

39:16.019 --> 39:17.100
What do you think would have happened?

39:17.120 --> 39:30.173
Do you think that the story would be that Jesus left him high and dry, that he actually lost everything of value in his life and made shipwreck of the things that he was doing, that it was the worst decision he ever made?

39:30.914 --> 39:33.076
I don't think that's the story that would have been written.

39:34.197 --> 39:35.378
In fact, I know it's not.

39:35.554 --> 39:43.507
I think the rich young ruler, we would have seen a story where he somehow started to inherit something far greater than he ever knew possible.

39:44.087 --> 39:50.377
Something far beyond his great dreams for his own life, of what action and adventure can be.

39:50.397 --> 39:56.787
I believe God would have been proven faithful that he would have received more than he desired.

39:56.827 --> 39:58.750
In fact, Jesus actually speaks to that.

39:59.412 --> 40:03.538
He says that his kingdom is a lot like somebody who finds a treasure

40:03.874 --> 40:10.982
and then buries it in a field and then goes and sells everything they have just to be able to purchase that little plot of land with the treasure in it.

40:11.262 --> 40:18.130
Because the kingdom that Jesus offers is like that treasure that's far beyond the value of anything else we can quantify.

40:18.610 --> 40:19.711
It's so worth it.

40:19.751 --> 40:23.235
You would sell everything you have just to have it because you know it's true value.

40:24.096 --> 40:25.938
And you'd actually walk away ahead in the end.

40:27.480 --> 40:32.946
He uses other stories of that same nature and it comes in with risk.

40:33.730 --> 40:40.660
that you and I are invited to leave the space of what is comfortable and choose faithful risk.

40:41.320 --> 40:57.423
So I wonder what embracing risk would look like for you and for me even in a season like this one, even when we're reeling from the memories of 9-11 and we're reflecting this weekend on what that tragic day meant 20 years ago and still means today.

40:58.043 --> 40:59.986
What would it look like to embrace risk

41:00.194 --> 41:07.426
and care for one another, even as we're walking through a season of transition as Heritage Church and seeking God's best now and next.

41:07.446 --> 41:18.283
What would it look like in your family life for you to choose the space of risk together rather than chasing after what is comfortable alone?

41:19.845 --> 41:20.687
Here's the truth, friends.

41:20.727 --> 41:22.770
We don't have to walk away sad.

41:23.106 --> 41:23.867
We don't have to.

41:23.907 --> 41:30.876
We're actually invited to live into adventure as we move from what we're owed to what we surrender from where there's comfort to what is risky.

41:31.197 --> 41:36.164
And then as we move from cold observance to passionate pursuit.

41:37.726 --> 41:41.651
This is part of what was happening in the story of the rich young ruler.

41:42.292 --> 41:47.579
You see, Jesus said, hey, you know what it means to start chasing after the things of God, don't you?

41:48.200 --> 41:51.604
And he lists a series of commandments from the Old Testament.

41:51.644 --> 41:52.946
And the rich young ruler says,

41:53.154 --> 41:55.658
All of these, each of them, I've kept them since I was a boy.

41:56.739 --> 42:01.907
And then Jesus says, okay, then do this next thing and come chase after me.

42:02.948 --> 42:03.689
Come follow me.

42:04.911 --> 42:05.772
Watch what happens.

42:07.595 --> 42:17.770
And I think part of the rich young ruler, this young man's challenge was that he didn't know how to move from cold observance to passionate pursuit.

42:18.511 --> 42:20.754
I think that for some of us, it's easy to think,

42:20.866 --> 42:24.810
God unlocking adventure in our lives is all about checking the right boxes.

42:25.391 --> 42:34.220
Or even God answering our deepest prayers and needs is about the right boxes being checked in our relationship with Him.

42:34.240 --> 42:47.675
If we pray the right prayers, if we read the right scriptures at the right time, if we sing the right songs and even serve in the right ways, if we check box one, two, three, and four, then we're guaranteed an outcome.

42:49.217 --> 42:50.418
That's not how this works.

42:51.010 --> 42:53.314
because it's not about cold observance.

42:53.594 --> 42:58.342
It's not about doing the right things for the sake of saying we've done them.

42:58.562 --> 43:10.923
It's actually about what does it look like to pursue the person of Jesus, his life, his way of breathing through us as we seek him, he leads us into adventure.

43:12.265 --> 43:15.410
This is where so many of us get frustrated and offended.

43:16.066 --> 43:29.155
because we think that God again who maybe owes us something, that we've checked the right boxes, we've made our interaction with Jesus all about cold checking the box at church.

43:31.079 --> 43:35.890
And that's not the life of adventure and purpose and meaning that we're meant for.

43:36.834 --> 43:48.148
Sometimes the checking the boxes and the cold observance for us is really more about being afraid of doing the wrong thing instead of chasing after the best things.

43:49.950 --> 44:01.103
And so we kind of limit ourselves into these cold spaces when Jesus, his beating heart for us is to experience life and purpose as we've never known it before.

44:02.925 --> 44:06.770
The invitation from Jesus to the rich young man wasn't something that was cruel.

44:07.042 --> 44:09.365
No, it was an invitation to surrender.

44:09.425 --> 44:11.247
It was an invitation to sacred risk.

44:11.508 --> 44:17.996
It was an invitation for passionate pursuit of Jesus, knowing he was everything the man was looking for.

44:19.017 --> 44:26.207
And so I know for some of us, we can't say today, I want to passionately pursue Jesus.

44:27.068 --> 44:32.595
When we may not fully be aware of what that means, or we just know with integrity, that's not true.

44:33.656 --> 44:35.058
So I would challenge you with this.

44:36.034 --> 44:42.988
I think if your prayer could simply be God, I want to want to passionately pursue you.

44:44.511 --> 44:47.036
I want to want that.

44:47.277 --> 44:49.081
I don't want it yet, but I want to want it.

44:49.982 --> 44:53.590
Will you allow that to be something that's true for me?

44:53.650 --> 44:55.033
That is a prayer that he will answer.

44:55.874 --> 44:57.618
We don't have to walk away sad, friends.

44:58.018 --> 45:05.526
Now some of us, as I said, were so desperate for action and adventure that we end up bringing action with us wherever we go.

45:05.747 --> 45:11.473
And that's actually a symptom of it being missing in our own hearts and lives.

45:11.793 --> 45:16.579
Is when we bring action, or maybe I would say drama with us wherever we go.

45:17.240 --> 45:20.643
We gotta stir things up in order to make things thrilling.

45:20.663 --> 45:26.610
That's a symptom that maybe we haven't stepped into the adventurous life that God actually has for us.

45:27.010 --> 45:34.761
So we find invitation to bring other people into the drama of our lives and to get our own anxieties projected on others.

45:34.821 --> 45:42.172
And like if we're gonna be in a problem, everybody else needs to be in a problem because that's how the closest that we can get to adventure and action together.

45:42.432 --> 45:44.074
I wanna read this passage of scripture to you.

45:44.916 --> 45:52.386
It says, don't call everything a conspiracy like they do and don't live in dread of what frightens them.

45:53.969 --> 45:54.930
For those of us,

45:55.170 --> 45:57.612
who cultivate drama wherever we go.

45:57.653 --> 46:04.820
I think these words are for you and for me, that we don't need the false adventure of conspiracy.

46:04.860 --> 46:09.745
We don't need the thrill of anxiety or of dread.

46:10.005 --> 46:13.288
We simply need to receive the true call to adventure.

46:13.609 --> 46:14.970
We are to be people of truth.

46:15.350 --> 46:19.955
We are to be people of love who live out of that for the sake of something greater.

46:21.216 --> 46:22.898
We don't have to walk away sad.

46:24.450 --> 46:25.892
And so here's my question for you.

46:27.814 --> 46:31.098
Where are you tempted to walk away sad today?

46:33.040 --> 46:45.155
Where are you tempted to walk away sad, to miss the opportunity for true adventure and walk away experiencing something less than what God has for you?

46:45.796 --> 46:48.539
The disciples actually address this later on in the story.

46:48.940 --> 46:54.066
One of them says to Jesus after the rich young ruler walks away, he says, Jesus don't you know we've left everything to follow you?

46:54.786 --> 46:57.310
And here's what Jesus responds in Mark chapter 10.

46:57.351 --> 47:07.529
He says, truly I tell you, no one who has left home or brothers or sisters or mother or father or children or fields for me and the gospel will fail to receive a hundred times as much in this present age.

47:08.230 --> 47:15.202
Homes, brothers, sisters, mothers, children and fields, along with persecutions and in the age to come eternal life.

47:16.505 --> 47:19.570
Many who are first will be last and the last first.

47:20.546 --> 47:31.599
Jesus is giving a survey of the things I think that he's saying, listen, these are the good things I've given that can actually cause you to walk away sad if they're not laid down in submission to me.

47:31.860 --> 47:38.988
These are spaces for you where you can surrender, where you can risk, where you can pursue with confidence.

47:40.370 --> 47:47.378
So I'm asking you, where are you tempted to walk away sad and there, there you may just receive the gift that he has for you.

47:48.546 --> 47:49.427
Don't walk away sad.

47:49.447 --> 47:56.117
Don't live another day distant from the adventure and the purpose and the meaning that you were meant for.

47:58.100 --> 48:09.597
Receive the gift that Jesus offers of his life by asking him to be the one who forgives and leads you, who is trustworthy with all of that and more that we just listed.

48:10.578 --> 48:16.147
And find what adventure looks like as he leads you forward.

48:17.649 --> 48:18.450
Let's pray together.

48:19.682 --> 48:21.144
Father, Son, and Spirit.

48:22.966 --> 48:36.384
Jesus, I thank you that we don't have to walk away sad, that the invitation you give us to adventure, to purpose, to meaning, Lord, that it's true and good and right, even now, right here.

48:37.585 --> 48:44.174
I pray for my friends, Lord, that you would reveal to us the spaces where, God, we long for adventure.

48:46.277 --> 48:47.378
And we've been disappointed.

48:49.730 --> 48:57.946
And there you want to meet us and breathe life into us and move us toward what is true and right and good.

48:59.829 --> 49:00.931
Lead us even now, we pray.

49:00.971 --> 49:05.259
Lead us in the space of action and adventure for the sake of something greater than ourselves.

49:05.961 --> 49:07.263
We pray this in Jesus' name.

49:08.385 --> 49:08.786
Amen.

49:25.058 --> 49:44.754
To you, my class, en la verceda, la solas con maras, tu bolde,

58:23.106 --> 58:24.948
Hey Heritage, thanks for worshiping with us today.

58:25.009 --> 58:33.039
I'm so thankful for this platform and this opportunity that we have each and every week to connect with God, each other, and our purpose virtually.

58:33.760 --> 58:37.365
Now, I love that song we just sing about, about God's love.

58:37.766 --> 58:47.499
Really, for me, it's just a great reminder of how vast God's love is for me and those around me and how now I'm called to take that love and bring to every sphere that God places in my path.

58:48.460 --> 58:50.002
Now, if you're joining today and

58:50.082 --> 58:54.327
And any questions came to mind or maybe you just realized that you really need prayer with someone.

58:55.208 --> 59:02.437
Or maybe you want to talk with a pastor, you can actually go to HeritageQC.com or call our church office and they can connect you with our prayer with their pastor line.

59:02.797 --> 59:06.281
And we would love to connect with you and journey with you and what you're going through.

59:09.806 --> 59:16.754
You know, I love that we are so invested as a church in these Quad Cities and meeting some real tangible needs of those who are in need.

59:17.026 --> 59:26.496
One of the ways that we are able to do that is because of your faithfulness and your generosity through giving financially and giving of your time and prayer and discernment with us.

59:27.117 --> 59:31.421
If you'd like to give to help with those things, go to heritageqc.com slash give.

59:32.202 --> 59:37.768
Another way that we connect as a church that I am so proud of is giving of our time.

59:38.028 --> 59:40.611
As Christ far as we are called a give of ourselves in many ways.

59:41.191 --> 59:43.794
One of the ways that you and your family can do that in this season

59:43.970 --> 59:48.355
is on Saturday, September 25th with our mobile food pantry.

59:48.615 --> 59:53.781
It's gonna be an awesome time of serving those in need who have tangible needs that need to be met.

59:54.041 --> 59:55.123
And you get to be a part of that.

59:55.523 --> 01:00:02.130
You can just go to heritageqc.com to register your church center app, or you can even call our church office line and we can get you connected in that way.

01:00:04.433 --> 01:00:08.818
Again, it was an awesome time worshiping with you and we'll see you all again next week.

